[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The principal designers of the C# programming language were Anders Hejlsberg, Scott Wiltamuth, and Peter Golde from Microsoft.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] It was first widely distributed in July 2000 and was later approved as an international standard by Ecma (ECMA-334) in 2002 and ISO/IEC (ISO/IEC 23270 and 20619) in 2003.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft introduced C# along with .NET Framework and Microsoft Visual Studio, both of which are, technically speaking, closed-source.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] At the time, Microsoft had no open-source products.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Four years later, in 2004, a free and open-source project called Mono began, providing a cross-platform compiler and runtime environment for the C# programming language.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft released Visual Studio Code (code editor), Roslyn (compiler), and the unified .NET platform (software framework), all of which support C# and are free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono also joined Microsoft, but was not merged into .NET.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] As of November 2025, the most recent stable version of the language is C# 14.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] During the development of the .NET Framework, the class libraries were originally written using a managed code compiler system named *Simple Managed C* (SMC).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In January 1999, Anders Hejlsberg formed a team to build a new language at the time called COOL, which stood for "C-like Object Oriented Language".
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft had considered keeping the name "COOL(C-like Object Oriented Language)" as the final name of the language, but chose not to do so for trademark reasons.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] By the time the .NET project was publicly announced at the July 2000 Professional Developers Conference, the language had been renamed C#, and the class libraries and ASP.NET runtime were ported to C#.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Hejlsberg was C#'s principal designer and lead architect at Microsoft, and had been previously involved with the design of Turbo Pascal, Embarcadero Delphi (formerly CodeGear Delphi, Inprise Delphi and Borland Delphi), and Visual J++.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In interviews and technical papers, he has stated that flaws in most major programming languages (e.g.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C++, Java, Delphi, and Smalltalk) drove the fundamentals of the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which, in turn, drove the design of the C# language.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2000, Hejlsberg said that C# is "not a Java clone" and is "much closer to C++" in its design.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Since the release of C# 2.0 in November 2005, the C# and Java languages have evolved on increasingly divergent trajectories, becoming two quite different languages.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] One of the first major departures came with the addition of generics to both languages, with vastly different implementations.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# uses reification to provide "first-class" generic objects that can be used like any other class, with code generation performed at class-load time.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has also added several major features to accommodate functional-style programming, culminating in the LINQ extensions released with C# 3.0 and its supporting framework of lambda expressions, extension methods, and anonymous types.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] These features enable C# programmers to use functional programming techniques, such as closures, when it is advantageous to their application.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# used to have a mascot called Andy (named after Anders Hejlsberg).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# was originally submitted to the ISO/IEC JTC 1 subcommittee SC 22 for review, under ISO/IEC 23270:2003, was withdrawn and was then approved under ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The 23270:2006 is withdrawn under 23270:2018 and approved with this version.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft first used the name C# in 1988 for a variant of the C language designed for incremental compilation.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] That project was not completed, and the name was later reused.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The name "C sharp" was inspired by the musical notation whereby a sharp symbol indicates that the written note should be made a semitone higher in pitch.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This is similar to the language name of C++, where "++" indicates that a variable should be incremented by 1 after being evaluated.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The sharp symbol also resembles a ligature of four "+" symbols (in a two-by-two grid), further implying that the language is an increment of C++.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to technical limits of display (standard fonts, browsers, etc.), and most keyboard layouts lacking a sharp symbol (U+266F ♯ MUSIC SHARP SIGN (&sharp;)), the number sign (U+0023 # NUMBER SIGN (&num;)) was chosen to approximate the sharp symbol in the written name of the programming language.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This convention is reflected in the ECMA-334 C# Language Specification.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The "sharp" suffix has been used by a number of other Microsoft .NET compatible/compliant languages that are variants of existing languages, including J# (a .NET language also designed by Microsoft that is derived from Java 1.1), A# (from Ada), and the functional programming language F#.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The original implementation of Eiffel for .NET was called Eiffel#, a name retired since the full Eiffel language is now supported.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The suffix has also been used for libraries, such as Gtk# (a .NET wrapper for GTK and other GNOME libraries) and Cocoa# (a wrapper for Cocoa).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Development of the text for standards (beginning with C# 6) is done on GitHub.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# 7 was submitted to Ecma and approved in December 2023.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] As of January 2024, the standard for C# 8 is currently under development, referencing the approved language proposals.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] By design, C# is the programming language that most directly reflects the underlying Common Language Infrastructure (CLI).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of its intrinsic types correspond to value-types implemented by the CLI framework.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the language specification does not state the code generation requirements of the compiler: that is, it does not state that a C# compiler must target a Common Language Runtime (CLR), or generate Common Intermediate Language (CIL), or generate any other specific format.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Some C# compilers can also generate machine code like traditional compilers of Objective-C, C, C++, Assembly and Fortran.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports strongly, implicitly typed variable declarations with the keyword `var`, and implicitly typed arrays with the keyword `new[]` followed by a collection initializer.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to their special handling of the equality operator and their immutability, strings will nevertheless behave as if they were values, for all practical purposes.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The programmer can even use them as case labels.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Where necessary, value types will be boxed automatically.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports a strict Boolean data type, `bool`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Statements that take conditions, such as `while` and `if`, require an expression of a type that evaluates to the `true` boolean value.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] While C++ also has a Boolean type, it can be freely converted to and from integers, and expressions such as `if (a)` require only that `a` is convertible to bool, allowing `a` to be an int, or a pointer.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# disallows this "integer meaning true or false" approach, on the grounds that forcing programmers to use expressions that return exactly `bool` can prevent certain types of programming mistakes such as `if (a = b)` (use of assignment `=` instead of equality `==`).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The only implicit conversions by default are those that are considered safe, such as widening of integers.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This is enforced at compile-time, during Just-in-time compilation, and, in some cases, at runtime.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] No implicit conversions occur between Booleans and integers, nor between enumeration members and integers (except for literal 0, which can be implicitly converted to any enumerated type).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Any user-defined conversion must be explicitly marked as explicit or implicit, unlike C++ copy constructors and conversion operators, which are both implicit by default.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has explicit support for covariance and contravariance in generic types, unlike C++ which has some degree of support for contravariance simply through the semantics of return types on virtual methods.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Enumeration members are placed in their own scope.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language does not allow for global variables or functions.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] All methods and members must be declared within classes.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Static members of public classes can substitute for global variables and functions.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Local variables cannot shadow variables of the enclosing block, unlike C and C++, but may shadow type-level names.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A *method* in C# is a member of a class that can be invoked as a function, rather than the mere value-holding capability of a *field*, i.e., class or instance variable.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Different from most other languages, call-by-reference parameters have to be marked both at the function definition and at the calling site, and the programmer can choose between `ref` and `out`, the latter allowing handing over an uninitialized variable which will have a definite value on return.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Additionally, the programmer can specify a variable-sized argument list by applying the `params` keyword to the last parameter.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Certain specific kinds of methods, such as those that simply get or set a field's value by returning or assigning it, do not require an explicitly stated full signature, but in the general case, the definition of a class includes the full signature declaration of its methods.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike Java, C# programmers must use the scope modifier keyword `virtual` to allow methods to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, the programmer must explicitly specify the keyword `override` when doing so.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This is supposed to avoid confusion between overriding and newly overloading a function, i.e., hiding the former implementation.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] To do the latter, the programmer has to specify the `new` keyword.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The keyword `sealed` can be used to disallow further overrides for individual methods or whole classes.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The type `dynamic` allows for run-time method binding, allowing for JavaScript-like method calls and run-time object composition.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has support for strongly-typed function pointers via the keyword `delegate`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Like the Qt framework's pseudo-C++ *signal* and *slot*, C# has semantics specifically surrounding publish-subscribe style events, though C# uses delegates to do so.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike fields, `event` variables can be part of an interface, because they technically consist of two default functions to add and remove to-be-called delegates.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# offers Java-like `synchronized` method calls, via the attribute `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.Synchronized)]`, and has support for mutually-exclusive locks via the keyword `lock`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The properties can be simple accessor functions with a backing field, or implement arbitrary getter and setter functions.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A property is read-only if there's no setter.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Like with fields, there can be class and instance properties.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The underlying methods can be `virtual` or `abstract` like any other method.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Since C# 3.0 the syntactic sugar of auto-implemented properties is available, where the accessor (getter) and mutator (setter) encapsulate operations on a single field of a class.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A C# `namespace` provides the same level of code isolation as a Java `package` or a C++ `namespace`, with rules and features very similar to a `package`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Namespaces can be imported with the "using" syntax.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In C#, memory address pointers can only be used within blocks specifically marked as *unsafe*, and programs with unsafe code need appropriate permissions to run.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Most object access is done through safe object references, which always either point to a "live" object or have the well-defined null value; it is impossible to obtain a reference to a "dead" object (one that has been garbage collected), or to an arbitrary block of memory.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] An unsafe pointer can point to an instance of an unmanaged value type that does not contain any references to objects subject to garbage collections such as class instances, arrays or strings.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that is not marked as unsafe can still store and manipulate pointers through the `System.IntPtr` type, but it cannot dereference them.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Managed memory cannot be explicitly freed; instead, it is automatically garbage collected.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Garbage collection addresses the problem of memory leaks by freeing the programmer of responsibility for releasing memory that is no longer needed in most cases.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that retains references to objects longer than is required can still experience higher memory usage than necessary, however once the final reference to an object is released the memory is available for garbage collection.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A range of standard exceptions are available to programmers.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Methods in standard libraries regularly throw system exceptions in some circumstances and the range of exceptions thrown is normally documented.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Custom exception classes can be defined for classes allowing handling to be put in place for particular circumstances as needed.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This is usually called a "try-catch" code block, because of the "try" and "catch" functions being used and accessible on all C# versions.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] If inspecting the error details is not required, the `(Exception ex)` parameter can be omitted as well.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Also, there can be several "catch" parts handling different kinds of exceptions.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Checked exceptions are not present in C# (in contrast to Java).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This has been a conscious decision based on the issues of scalability and version management.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, C# does not support multiple inheritance, although a class can implement any number of "interfaces" (fully abstract classes).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This was a design decision by the language's lead architect to avoid complications and to simplify architectural requirements throughout CLI.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] When implementing multiple interfaces that contain a method with the same name and taking parameters of the same types in the same order, i.e., the same signature, similar to Java, C# allows both a single method to cover all interfaces and, if necessary, specific methods for each interface.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# also offers function overloading (a.k.a. ad-hoc-polymorphism), i.e., methods with the same name, but distinguishable signatures.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike Java, C# additionally supports operator overloading.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Since version 2.0, C# offers parametric polymorphism, i.e., classes with arbitrary or constrained type parameters, e.g., `List<T>`, a variable-sized array which only can contain elements of type `T`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] There are certain kinds of constraints the programmer can specify for the type parameters: Has to be type X (or one derived from it), has to implement a certain interface, has to be a reference type, has to be a value type, has to implement a public parameterless constructor.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of them can be combined, and any number of interfaces can be specified.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has the ability to utilize LINQ through the .NET Framework.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A developer can query a variety of data sources, provided the `IEnumerable<T>` interface is implemented on the object.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This includes XML documents, an ADO.NET dataset, and SQL databases.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Using LINQ in C# brings advantages like IntelliSense support, strong filtering capabilities, type safety with compile error checking ability, and consistency for querying data over a variety of sources.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] There are several different language structures that can be utilized with C# and LINQ and they are query expressions, lambda expressions, anonymous types, implicitly typed variables, extension methods, and object initializers.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] LINQ has two syntaxes: query syntax and method syntax.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the compiler always converts the query syntax to method syntax at compile time.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This unified type system is called Common Type System (CTS).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A unified type system implies that all types, including primitives such as integers, are subclasses of the `System.Object` class.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, every type inherits a `ToString()` method.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Instances of value types neither have referential identity nor referential comparison semantics.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Equality and inequality comparisons for value types compare the actual data values within the instances, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Value types are derived from `System.ValueType`, always have a default value, and can always be created and copied.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Other examples are `enum` (enumerations) and `struct` (user defined structures).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In contrast, reference types have the notion of referential identity, meaning that each instance of a reference type is inherently distinct from every other instance, even if the data within both instances is the same.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This is reflected in default equality and inequality comparisons for reference types, which test for referential rather than structural equality, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded (such as the case for `System.String`).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Some operations are not always possible, such as creating an instance of a reference type, copying an existing instance, or performing a value comparison on two existing instances.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Nevertheless, specific reference types can provide such services by exposing a public constructor or implementing a corresponding interface (such as `ICloneable` or `IComparable`).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Examples of reference types are `object` (the ultimate base class for all other C# classes), `System.String` (a string of Unicode characters), and `System.Array` (a base class for all C# arrays).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Both type categories are extensible with user-defined types.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# specification details a minimum set of types and class libraries that the compiler expects to have available.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In practice, C# is most often used with some implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI), which is standardized as ECMA-335 *Common Language Infrastructure (CLI)*.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In addition to the standard CLI specifications, there are many commercial and community class libraries that build on top of the .NET framework libraries to provide additional functionality.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# can make calls to any library included in the List of .NET libraries and frameworks.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The line above imports all types in the `System` namespace.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, the `Console` class used later in the source code is defined in the `System` namespace, meaning it can be used without supplying the full name of the type (which includes the namespace).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This line is a comment; it describes and documents the code for the programmer(s).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Above is a class definition for the `Program` class.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Everything that follows between the pair of braces describes that class.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The curly brackets demarcate the boundaries of a code block.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In this first instance, they are marking the start and end of the `Program` class.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This declares the class member method where the program begins execution.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The .NET runtime calls the `Main` method.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike in Java, the `Main` method does not need the `public` keyword, which tells the compiler that the method can be called from anywhere by any class.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Writing `static void Main(string[] args)` is equivalent to writing `private static void Main(string[] args)`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The static keyword makes the method accessible without an instance of `Program`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Each console application's `Main` entry point must be declared `static` otherwise the program would require an instance of `Program`, but any instance would require a program.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] To avoid that irresolvable circular dependency, C# compilers processing console applications (like that above) report an error if there is no `static Main` method.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The `void` keyword declares that `Main` has no return value.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] `Console` is a static class in the `System` namespace.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] It provides an interface to the standard input/output, and error streams for console applications.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The program calls the `Console` method `WriteLine`, which displays on the console a line with the argument, the string `"Hello, World!"`.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] With .NET 2.0 and C# 2.0, the community got more flexible collections than those in .NET 1.x.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In the absence of generics, developers had to use collections such as ArrayList to store elements as objects of unspecified kind, which incurred performance overhead when boxing/unboxing/type-checking the contained items.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Generics introduced a massive new feature in .NET that allowed developers to create type-safe data structures.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] This shift is particularly important in the context of converting legacy systems, where updating to generics can significantly enhance performance and maintainability by replacing outdated data structures with more efficient, type-safe alternatives.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In August 2001, Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Intel co-sponsored the submission of specifications for C# as well as the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) to the standards organization Ecma International.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In December 2001, ECMA released ECMA-334 *C# Language Specification*.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] C# became an ISO/IEC standard in 2003 (ISO/IEC 23270:2003 - *Information technology — Programming languages — C#*).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] ECMA had previously adopted equivalent specifications as the 2nd edition of C#, in December 2002.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In June 2005, ECMA approved edition 3 of the C# specification, and updated ECMA-334.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Additions included partial classes, anonymous methods, nullable types, and generics (somewhat similar to C++ templates).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2005, ECMA submitted to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22, via the latter's Fast-Track process, the standards and related TRs.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language definition and the CLI are standardized under ISO/IEC and Ecma standards that provide reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing protection from patent claims.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft initially agreed not to sue open-source developers for violating patents in non-profit projects for the part of the framework that is covered by the Open Specification Promise.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has also agreed not to enforce patents relating to Novell products against Novell's paying customers with the exception of a list of products that do not explicitly mention C#, .NET or Novell's implementation of .NET (The Mono Project).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] However, Novell maintained that Mono does not infringe any Microsoft patents.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft also made a specific agreement not to enforce patent rights related to the Moonlight browser plugin, which depends on Mono, provided it is obtained through Novell.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft began developing free, open-source, and cross-platform tooling for C#, namely Visual Studio Code, .NET Core, and Roslyn.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono joined Microsoft as a project of Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has developed open-source reference C# compilers and tools.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The first compiler, Roslyn, compiles into intermediate language (IL), and the second one, RyuJIT, is a JIT (just-in-time) compiler, which is dynamic and does on-the-fly optimization and compiles the IL into native code for the front-end of the CPU.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] RyuJIT is open source and written in C++.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Roslyn is entirely written in managed code (C#), has been opened up and functionality surfaced as APIs.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] It is thus enabling developers to create refactoring and diagnostics tools.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] Two branches of official implementation are .NET Framework (closed-source, Windows-only) and .NET Core (open-source, cross-platform); they eventually converged into one open-source implementation: .NET 5.0.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] At .NET Framework 4.6, a new JIT compiler replaced the former.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The Unity game engine uses C# as its primary scripting language.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/c-sharp-programming-language] The Godot game engine has implemented an optional C# module due to a donation of $24,000 from Microsoft.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] The concept was introduced by David Heinemeier Hansson to describe the philosophy of the Ruby on Rails web framework, but is related to earlier ideas like the concept of "sensible defaults" and the principle of least astonishment in user interface design.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] The phrase essentially means a developer only needs to specify unconventional aspects of the application.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] For example, if there is a class Sales in the model, the corresponding table in the database is called "sales" by default.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] It is only if one deviates from this convention, such as the table "product sales", that one needs to write code regarding these names.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] When the convention implemented by the tool matches the desired behavior, it behaves as expected without having to write configuration files.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Only when the desired behavior deviates from the implemented convention is explicit configuration required.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Ruby on Rails' use of the phrase is particularly focused on its default project file and directory structure, which prevent developers from having to write XML configuration files to specify which modules the framework should load, which was common in many earlier frameworks.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Other methods of decreasing the number of decisions a developer needs to make include programming idioms and configuration libraries with a multilayered architecture.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Some frameworks need multiple configuration files, each with many settings.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] These provide information specific to each project, ranging from URLs to mappings between classes and database tables.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Many configuration files with many parameters are often difficult to maintain.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] For example, early versions of the Java persistence mapper Hibernate mapped entities and their fields to the database by describing these relationships in XML files.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Most of this information could have been revealed by conventionally mapping class names to the identically named database tables and the fields to their columns, respectively.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Later versions did away with the XML configuration file and instead employed these very conventions, deviations from which can be indicated through the use of Java annotations (see JavaBeans specification, linked below).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] Many modern frameworks use a *convention over configuration* approach.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] The concept is older, however, dating back to the concept of a default, and can be spotted more recently in the roots of Java libraries.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/convention-over-configuration] For example, the JavaBeans specification relies on it heavily.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] In the field of programming a **data transfer object** (**DTO**) is an object that carries data between processes.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] The motivation for its use is that communication between processes is usually done resorting to remote interfaces (e.g., web services), where each call is an expensive operation.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] The difference between data transfer objects and business objects or data access objects is that a DTO does not have any behavior except for storage, retrieval, serialization and deserialization of its own data (mutators, accessors, serializers and parsers).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] In other words, DTOs are simple objects that should not contain any business logic but may contain serialization and deserialization mechanisms for transferring data over the wire.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] This pattern is often incorrectly used outside of remote interfaces.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] This has triggered a response from its author where he reiterates that the whole purpose of DTOs is to shift data in expensive remote calls.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] The two terms have been conflated by Sun/Java community in the past.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/data-transfer-object] For the model–view–viewmodel pattern, the data transfer object can be referred to as the viewmodel.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In computer science, **reflective programming** or **reflection** is the ability of a process to examine, introspect, and modify its own structure and behavior.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] The earliest computers were programmed in their native assembly languages, which were inherently reflective, as these original architectures could be programmed by defining instructions as data and using self-modifying code.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] As the bulk of programming moved to higher-level compiled languages such as ALGOL, COBOL, Fortran, Pascal, and C, this reflective ability largely disappeared until new programming languages with reflection built into their type systems appeared.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Brian Cantwell Smith's 1982 doctoral dissertation introduced the notion of computational reflection in procedural programming languages and the notion of the meta-circular interpreter as a component of 3-Lisp.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection helps programmers make generic software libraries to display data, process different formats of data, perform serialization and deserialization of data for communication, or do bundling and unbundling of data for containers or bursts of communication.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflective systems may provide a mirror type, used as a decoupled reflection of an object or identifier.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Effective use of reflection almost always requires a plan: A design framework, encoding description, object library, a map of a database or entity relations.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection makes a language more suited to network-oriented code.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] For example, it assists languages such as Java to operate well in networks by enabling libraries for serialization, bundling and varying data formats.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Languages without reflection such as C are required to use auxiliary compilers for tasks like Abstract Syntax Notation to produce code for serialization and bundling.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be used for observing and modifying program execution at runtime.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A reflection-oriented program component can monitor the execution of an enclosure of code and can modify itself according to a desired goal of that enclosure.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] This is typically accomplished by dynamically assigning program code at runtime.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In object-oriented programming languages such as Java, reflection allows *inspection* of classes, interfaces, fields and methods at runtime without knowing the names of the interfaces, fields, methods at compile time.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] It also allows *instantiation* of new objects and *invocation* of methods.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is often used as part of software testing, such as for the runtime creation/instantiation of mock objects.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is also a key strategy for metaprogramming.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In some object-oriented programming languages such as C# and Java, reflection can be used to bypass member accessibility rules.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] For C#-properties this can be achieved by writing directly onto the (usually invisible) backing field of a non-public property.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] It is also possible to find non-public methods of classes and types and manually invoke them.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] This works for project-internal files as well as external libraries such as .NET's assemblies and Java's archives.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A language that supports reflection provides a number of features available at runtime that would otherwise be difficult to accomplish in a lower-level language.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] These features can be implemented in different ways.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In MOO, reflection forms a natural part of everyday programming idiom.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] When verbs (methods) are called, various variables such as `verb` (the name of the verb being called) and `this` (the object on which the verb is called) are populated to give the context of the call.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Compiled languages rely on their runtime system to provide information about the source code.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A compiled Objective-C executable, for example, records the names of all methods in a block of the executable, providing a table to correspond these with the underlying methods (or selectors for these methods) compiled into the program.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In a compiled language that supports runtime creation of functions, such as Common Lisp, the runtime environment must include a compiler or an interpreter.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be implemented for languages without built-in reflection by using a program transformation system to define automated source-code changes.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection may allow a user to create unexpected control flow paths through an application, potentially bypassing security measures.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Historical vulnerabilities in Java caused by unsafe reflection allowed code retrieved from potentially untrusted remote machines to break out of the Java sandbox security mechanism.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A large scale study of 120 Java vulnerabilities in 2013 concluded that unsafe reflection is the most common vulnerability in Java, though not the most exploited.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Runtime reflection systems introduce a non-negligible runtime performance overhead.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] For instance, in Java, because reflective operations are resolved dynamically at execution time, many compiler and JVM optimizations—such as method inlining, static binding, and aggressive just-in-time specialization—cannot be fully applied.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] As a consequence, reflective calls are typically slower than their statically resolved counterparts.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In sequential applications, reflection can significantly increase execution time and memory consumption when used in performance-critical code paths.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In multithreaded applications, reflective implementations generally preserve scalability, but still exhibit noticeably higher absolute execution times—commonly between 1.5x and 10× slower—than equivalent non-reflective code.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In languages like C++ and Rust, reflection is performed at compile time.
[src:automapper-dotnet-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Compile-time reflection systems are weaker than runtime reflection systems like those of Java and C#, but incur no runtime overhead due to being performed during compilation.
